026|/// The callback function used in clone system call. The return value is i32
027|/// which is consistent with C functions return code. The trait has to be
028|/// `FnMut` because we need to be able to call the closure multiple times, once
029|/// in clone3 and once in clone if fallback is required. The closure is boxed
030|/// because we need to store the closure on heap, not stack in the case of
031|/// `clone`. Unlike `fork` or `clone3`, the `clone` glibc wrapper requires us to
032|/// pass in a child stack, which is empty. By storing the closure in heap, we
033|/// can then in the new process to re-box the heap memory back to a closure
034|/// correctly.
035|pub type CloneCb<'a> = Box<dyn FnMut() -> i32 + 'a>;
036|
037|// Clone a sibling process that shares the same parent as the calling
038|// process. This is used to launch the container init process so the parent
039|// process of the calling process can receive ownership of the process. If we
040|// clone a child process as the init process, the calling process (likely the
041|// youki main process) will exit and the init process will be re-parented to the
042|// process 1 (system init process), which is not the right behavior of what we
043|// look for.
044|pub fn container_clone_sibling(cb: CloneCb) -> Result<Pid, CloneError> {
045|    // Note: normally, an exit signal is required, but when using
046|    // `CLONE_PARENT`, the `clone3` will return EINVAL if an exit signal is set.
047|    // The older `clone` will not return EINVAL in this case. Instead it ignores
048|    // the exit signal bits in the glibc wrapper. Therefore, we explicitly set
049|    // the exit_signal to None here, so this works for both version of clone.
050|    clone_internal(cb, libc::CLONE_PARENT as u64, None)
051|}
